[[Image:Beresford Street Pitt Street 1920s.jpg|thumb|right|Historical company offices in the 1920s. The building on the corner of Beresford Street / Pitt Street still exists.]]

The '''Auckland Gas Company''' is a company providing [[Liquefied petroleum gas|gas]] for residential or commercial customers in the [[Auckland]] area, [[New Zealand]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}} It is one of the oldest still existing [[brand|brand names]] in New Zealand, having been established as Auckland Gas Company Ltd in 1862 or 1863.<ref>[http://www.aucklandgas.co.nz/why-agc/ Why The Auckland Gas Company?] (from the official company website. Accessed 2008-02-20.) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216155217/http://www.aucklandgas.co.nz/why-agc/ |date=February 16, 2008 }}</ref> It is owned since 2004 by [[Nova Energy]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}

== History ==

The Auckland Gas Company was formed in 1862 as the first [[joint stock company]] in New Zealand. It was also the first private services provider in Auckland. In the 1870s, the company bought and developed a large site in [[Freemans Bay]] to build a [[gasworks]] (roughly on and east of the site of the current [[New World (supermarket)|New World]] supermarket), with further buildings (mainly workshops) and offices on Beaumont Street.<ref name="TRAN">[http://cmi.transit.govt.nz/resources/vpt/Notice%20of%20Req/Volume%203/Appendix-16-Heritage.pdf Auckland Gas Company Offices and Workshops Buildings] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411172558/http://cmi.transit.govt.nz/resources/vpt/Notice%20of%20Req/Volume%203/Appendix-16-Heritage.pdf |date=April 11, 2008 }} (from the Addendum 2 February 2006 of the [[Victoria Park Viaduct|Vic Park Tunnel]] project documentation, [[Transit New Zealand]], Page 13. Accessed 2008-02-20.)</ref>

In the late 1960s the [[Kapuni]] gas fields were opened, providing [[natural gas]] which was cleaner and cheaper than the locally produced [[coal gas]] variant, and the company stopped producing gas and became a supplier only. This led to most of the buildings in the Freemans Bay are being demolished.<ref name="TRAN"/>

