{{Infobox lake |name = Grand Lake |image = Grand Lake.jpg |caption = looking east |image_bathymetry = |caption_bathymetry = |location = [[Grand County, Colorado]] |coords = {{coord|40|14|42|N|105|48|58|W|type:waterbody_region:US-CO|display=inline,title}} |lake_type = Glacial Lake |inflow = |outflow = |catchment = Native inflows come from the [[Continental Divide]] through [[Rocky Mountain National Park]]. |basin_countries = United States |length = {{convert|1.5|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name="Grand Lake Winter Adventure Tour">{{Cite web|title=Grand Lake Winter Adventure Tour|url=http://www.9news.com/advertorial/adventure/grandlake.asp}}</ref> |width = {{convert|1|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name="Grand Lake Winter Adventure Tour"/> |area = {{convert|507|acre|abbr=on}}<ref name=Lieberman>Lieberman, D.M. 2008. ''Physical, Chemical, and biological Attributes of Western and Eastern Slope Reservoir, Lake, and Flowing Water sites on the Colorado-Big Thompson Project 2005-2007: Lake Granby, Grand Lake, Shadow Mountain Reservoir, Horsetooth Reservoir, Carter Lake''. Denver Colorado: Department of Interior, Bureau of Reclamation; 469p</ref> |depth = |max-depth = {{convert|265|ft|abbr=on}}<ref name=Lieberman /> |volume ={{convert|68,621|acre.ft|abbr=on}}<ref name=Lieberman /> |shore = {{convert|4|mi|abbr=on}} (approx)<ref name=GC>Grand County Government</ref> |elevation = {{convert|8,367|ft|m|abbr=on}} |islands = |cities = [[Grand Lake, Colorado]] }}
'''Grand Lake''' is [[Colorado]]'s largest and deepest natural [[lake]].<ref>Pennak, R.W. 1955 ''Comparative Limnology of Eight Colorado Mountain Lakes.'' University of Colorado Studies, Series in Biology 2:1-71, Boulder, CO 1955</ref> It is located in the [[headwater]]s of the [[Colorado River]] in [[Grand County, Colorado]]. On its north shore is located the historic and eponymous town of [[Grand Lake, Colorado|Grand Lake]]. The lake fills a glaciated valley that is dammed in part by [[glacier|glacial]] [[till]] from the [[Pinedale Glaciation]], and is younger than about 12,000 years. Natural tributaries to the lake are the [[North Inlet]] and [[East Inlet]], both of which flow out of [[Rocky Mountain National Park]], which surrounds the lake on three sides: Grand Lake is located 1 mile from the Park's western entrance. Grand Lake was named Spirit Lake by the [[Ute Tribe]] because they believed the lake's cold waters to be the dwelling place of departed souls.
==Colorado-Big Thompson Project== As part of the [[Colorado-Big Thompson Project]], Grand Lake forms a continuous body of water with the man-made reservoir [[Shadow Mountain Lake]], which under natural conditions then flows into another man-made reservoir, [[Lake Granby]]. The elevation of Grand Lake is maintained between 8,367 feet (2,550 meters) and 8,366 feet (2,549.8 meters). When the Colorado-Big Thompson (C-BT) project is diverting water to northeastern Colorado, water collected in Lake Granby can be pumped back into Shadow Mountain where it flows backward into Grand Lake, then under [[Rocky Mountain National Park]] and the [[Continental Divide]] via the [[Alva B. Adams Tunnel]] to the [[Big Thompson River]] on the eastern slope of the [[Rocky Mountains]]. From there, the water flows into the [[South Platte River]] and is used for [[agriculture]], [[municipal]], and [[Industry|industrial]] purposes. Diverted C-BT water provides [[hydroelectric power]] to five [[power station]]s on the eastern slope of the Colorado Rockies.
The C-BT is one of the first of many large-scale diversions of water from the [[Colorado River Basin]] between [[Colorado]] and the [[Gulf of California]]. Because the C-BT Project moves water from the Colorado Basin to the South Platte Basin, or, on a larger scale, from the [[Colorado River]], which drains to the [[Gulf of California]] to the [[Mississippi River]], which drains to the [[Gulf of Mexico]], the project is considered a [[transbasin diversion]].
