'''HVDC BorWin3''' is a [[high voltage direct current]] (HVDC) link under construction to transmit [[Offshore wind power]] to the [[power grid]] of the [[Germany|German mainland]]. The project differs from most HVDC systems in that one of the two [[HVDC converter station|converter stations]] is built on a platform in the sea. [[HVDC converter#Voltage-Sourced Converter|Voltage-Sourced Converters]] with DC ratings of 900&nbsp;MW, ±320&nbsp;kV are used and the total cable length is 160&nbsp;km. The project is the most recent of the German offshore HVDC projects to be awarded (in 2014).<ref>[http://www.siemens.com/press/en/pressrelease/?press=/en/pressrelease/2014/energy/power-transmission/et201404036.htm Siemens receives major order for BorWin3 North Sea grid connection from TenneT], [[Siemens]] press Release, 15 April 2014.</ref> It is being built by the [[Siemens]]/ [[Petrofac]] consortium with the offshore platform contract awarded to Drydocks World in [[Dubai]].<ref>[http://www.drydocks.gov.ae/en/news/borwin.wind.aspx Drydocks World announces Signing Ceremony to build wind platform Borwin 3], Drydocks World website, 13 October 2014.</ref> The project is expected to be handed over to its owner, [[TenneT]], in 2019.
